## ***Please Upvote my solution, if you find it helpful ;)***

# Intuition
We are given a string s and an integer k. We need to find the maximum number of vowels in any substring of length k in the given string. We will use the sliding window technique to solve this problem. The sliding window is like a moving frame of fixed length (k) that slides through the string.
# Approach
1. Initialize a string vowel containing all the vowel characters.
1. Convert the input string s to a character array for easy access to individual characters.
1. Initialize variables max and count to keep track of the maximum count and current count of vowels, respectively.
1. Count the number of vowels in the first k characters of the string.
1. If k is greater than or equal to the length of the string, return the current count since the whole string is considered a substring.
1. Initialize two pointers, start and end, to represent the start and end indices of the sliding window.
1. Slide the window by incrementing start and end one step at a time.
1. Decrement the count if the character at the start of the window is a vowel and increment the count if the character at the end of the window is a vowel.
1. Update the maximum count whenever a new maximum is found.
1. Repeat steps 7-9 until the end of the string is reached.
1. Return the maximum count as the result.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The time complexity of this solution is $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input string. We slide the window through the string once, and the operations inside the loop take constant time.

- Space complexity:
The space complexity of your solution is $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input string s. This is because you are converting the string to a char array, which requires additional space to store the characters

# Code
```java []
class Solution {
    public int maxVowels(String s, int k) {
        // Define the string of vowels
        String vowel = "aeiouAEIOU";

        // Convert the input string to a character array
        char[] word = s.toCharArray();

        // Initialize variables to track maximum count and current count of vowels
        int max = 0;
        int count = 0;

        // Count the vowels in the first k characters
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            if (vowel.indexOf(word[i]) != -1) {
                count++;
            }
        }

        // If k is greater than or equal to the length of the string, return the current count
        if (k >= word.length) {
            return count;
        }

        // Initialize pointers for sliding window
        int start = 0;
        int end = k;

        // Update the maximum count with the initial count
        max = Math.max(max, count);

        // Slide the window and update the count of vowels
        while (end < word.length) {
            // Decrement count if the character at the start of the window is a vowel
            if (vowel.indexOf(word[start++]) != -1) {
                count--;
            }

            // Increment count if the character at the end of the window is a vowel
            if (vowel.indexOf(word[end++]) != -1) {
                count++;
            }

            // Update the maximum count
            max = Math.max(max, count);
        }

        // Return the maximum count of vowels
        return max;
    }
}
```
