# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
  In this question we need to find the maximum vowel , and the sliding window technique is a powerful approach to solve a wide range of problems where we need to find a maximum or minimum value in a substring of a given size.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize two pointers left and right to the beginning of the     string s.

    Calculate the vowel count for the first k characters in the string.

2. Initialize a variable "max_vowel" to the vowel count of the first k characters.

3. Move the window one character to the right by incrementing left and right pointers and updating the vowel count of the window.

4. Update "max_vowel" if the current vowel count is greater than the maximum seen so far.

5. Repeat step 4 and 5 until the end of the string is reached.

6. Return the maximum vowel count.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
  The time complexity of the above code is O(n) as we are iterating over the string only once. 

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) as we are only using a constant amount of extra space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxVowels(string s, int k) {
        int n = s.size();
        int max_vowel = 0 ; 
        int vowel_count = 0 ; 
        int right = 0 , left = 0 ; 

        while(right< n ){
            if(right - left < k ){
                if(s[right] =='a'|| s[right] == 'e' || s[right] =='i' || s[right] =='o' ||s[right] =='u'){
                    vowel_count++;}

                 right++;
            } else 
                   {
                max_vowel = max(max_vowel , vowel_count);
                if(s[left] =='a'|| s[left] == 'e' || s[left] =='i' || s[left] =='o' ||s[left] =='u')vowel_count--;
                left++;
            }

        }

       return max(max_vowel , vowel_count);
    }
};
