solutions.content:
Sweet example of a problem that can become rather easy once you have the experience and insight to break it into smaller bits.

We will declare a couple of variables as class variables to make our life easier:
* `res` will be our accumulator variable counting how many "palindromable" paths we find;
* `tmp` will allow us to build them as we go along.

Since we know we will never get any empty tree, in our main function we can just first of all call `dfs(root)`.

`dfs` is a function that receives only one parameter (and manipulates the two aforementioned class variables), `root`. Within it, we will:
* add `root` to `path`;
* check if the current node is a leaf and if so increase `res` if the current `path` is palindromable (more on it later on);
* call itself recursively on the `left` and `right` branch, provided they exist (so we can keep our invariant of assuming `root` will never be `NULL` in each successive call);
* backtrack, removing the current `root` from `path`.

The other helper function, `isPalindromable`, will receive itself only one parameter - `path` as populated in `dfs`.

In it we will declare 2 support variabless to check if a path can be turned into a palindrome or not:
* `check` is an array of 10 integers (I know we only needed `9`, but that saves a `-1` at each step, either now or when we build `path` - well worth a couple of extra bytes);
* `seenOdd`, a boolean to keep track of having already encountered a number with odd frequency (we can afford to have only one, if we put it in the middle of a palindrome, but no more than that).

We will then:
* populate `check` with the frequencies
* parse it; as mentioned, as soon as we find an odd number, we need to:
	* return `false` if we have already seen one;
	* turn `seenOdd` to `true` otherwise.
* If we go out of the loop safely, we can return `true`.

Once we are done running `dfs`, we can just return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int res = 0;
    vector<int> path;
    void dfs(TreeNode *root) {
        // updating path
        path.push_back(root->val);
        // checking when in a leaf
        if (!root->left && !root->right) res += isPalindromable(path);
        // exploring the branches
        if (root->left) dfs(root->left);
        if (root->right) dfs(root->right);
        // backtracking
        path.pop_back();
    }
    bool isPalindromable(vector<int> &path) {
        // support variables
        unsigned short check[10] = {};
        bool seenOdd = false;
        // populating check
        for (int n: path) check[n]++;
        // verifying if we have more than one odd
        for (int n: check) if (n % 2) {
            if (seenOdd) return false;
            seenOdd = true;
        }
        return true;
    }
    int pseudoPalindromicPaths(TreeNode *root) {
        dfs(root);
        return res;
    }
};
```

Was I happy with it? Nah: time to dust off my bitwise-fu and improve a bit.

I decided to turn `check` into `isPalindromable` to be just an `int`; for each number, we will XOR it with the matching bit from the right and in the end. we will just have to check if the number is a power of `2` (meaning we only had an odd frequency) or `0` (meanng no odd frequencies found at all).

To clarify with an example, let's consider parsing the tree you can generate with `[2,1,1,1,3,null,null,null,null,null,1,2,4]` and the 2 longest paths you will get out of it: `{2,1,3,1,2}` and `{2,1,3,1,4}`. I highlighted them in red and blue respectively here:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/55030120-ff08-4987-8e81-747b39ecbc7e_1609244067.9496357.png)

Now, moving with the first, we will have as values of `check`:

```cpp
0  // initial value
4  // after XORing 1 << 2 to it
6  // after XORing 1 << 1 to it
14 // after XORing 1 << 3 to it
12 // after XORing 1 << 1 to it
8  // after XORing 1 << 2 to it
```

And since `8` is indeed a power of `2`, we return `true`!

If you try with the other path, you will see that you will get a final result of `28` (`== (2 << 2) + (2 << 3) + ( 2 << 4)`, definitely not a power of `2`, so we can return `false` :)

The improved code, which uses a bit less memory and let me gain about 16ms on average:

```cpp
    bool isPalindromable(vector<int> &path) {
        // support variables
        int check = 0;
        // populating check
        for (int n: path) check ^= 1 << n;
        // verifying if we have more than one odd
        return !(check & (check - 1));
    }
```

At this point you might wonder "hey, wait a moment - do I still need to waste precious CPU and bytes in carrying around a cumbersome vector of ints as a path?".

Well, I did actually ask that myself and decided to cut the middlemen (sorry vector and sorry helper function: I am sure you will be fondly remembered by posterity, but I had to get rid of you) and finally I came up with a much lighter, faster and more efficient version of my code, going down to another best time of 164ms:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int res = 0;
    int path;
    void dfs(TreeNode *root) {
        // updating path
        path ^= 1 << root->val;
        // checking when in a leaf
        if (!root->left && !root->right) res += !(path & (path - 1));
        // exploring the branches
        if (root->left) dfs(root->left);
        if (root->right) dfs(root->right);
        // backtracking
        path ^= 1 << root->val;
    }
    int pseudoPalindromicPaths(TreeNode *root) {
        dfs(root);
        return res;
    }
};
```

