solutions.content:
This is an easy one! :) 

How can we check if any permutation of a number is palindrome ? 
```
1 2 3 2 1     Yes
1 2 2 1       Yes
1 1 1 1       Yes
1 2 1 1 2     No
```

**Observations**
Palindrome contains numbers in pair, correct ?
It can have atmost one single number which we can place in the middle ?  (1 2 **3** 2 1)

**How can we achieve this ?**
We can create a set - 
* Everytime we come across a number which is already present in set (We have found a pair !!), we can remove it from set 
* If a new number comes, we can add in set (A unique/single number as of this particular iteration)
* In the end, if our set becomes empty, means every number was in some pair (Palindrome!!)
* Or if the size of set is 1, means only one single number is left, it can be placed in the middle (Palindrome!!  eg ->  1 2 **3** 2 1 )


**Integrating this part with Tree Recursion**

We can access Path of Tree in any fashion, I have done this in Pre-Order

Coming across a node - 

**1st Step** :   null check 
**2nd Step**:  Above logic for set -> Check if set already contains that node or not 
```
  if(set.contains(root.val)) set.remove(root.val);
  else set.add(root.val);
```
**3rd Step**:  We need to check palindrome for every path of tree, means whenever we completes a path... i.e.  Whenever we come across a leaf node, right ?

```
if(root.left == null && root.right == null){
            if(set.size() == 1 || set.isEmpty()) res++;
}
```

**4th Step**:  Tree Treaversal (left and right subtrees)
```
util(root.left, set);
util(root.right, set);
```
**5th Step**:  *Backtracking Step* -> After accessing a particular path, when going back, we should discard the current no, right ? So, modify the set, right

* Our set takes care of duplicate values
```
        2
	  /   \
	 3      1
	/ \      \
   3   1      1
```

* So, First path will be **(2 3 3)**
* After processing last 3 here, our set will contain **[2]** based on above logic (as we have two occurences of 3)
* So, while going back, we need to add a 3 in the set, because for the other path **(2 3 1)** this 3 will not be a duplicate value 
* Now for the second path (2 3 1), while going back, our set will contain **[2 3 1]** (all uniques), so we can simply remove 1 from the set 

**So final logic comes as** : If set does not contains the value, add it in set, if it contains, remove it . 

This sums up the question!
**Please do a dry-run for clear understanding!!**

