This is a interesting question with interesting trick: n&(n-1) to check at most one odd occurence of number.

To get some quick idea what is the trick, let's check the following 3 examples illustrated in the table:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/codedayday/image_1590347110.png)


**Version 3: 4-line solution with comments**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int pseudoPalindromicPaths (TreeNode* root, int cnt = 0) {
        if(!root) return 0;                
        cnt ^= 1 << (root->val - 1); //Flips the (root.val-1)th bit, indicating the even/odd occurrence of corresponding bit
        if(root->left == root->right && (cnt & (cnt - 1)) == 0) return 1; //cnt & (cnt - 1) being 0 means at most 1 num has odd occurence
		//if(!root->left && !root->right) return __builtin_popcount(cnt)<=1; //ok, in case the above-line is hard
        return pseudoPalindromicPaths(root->left, cnt) + pseudoPalindromicPaths(root->right, cnt);        
    }
};
```
