**Complete beginner-friendly, easy to understand solution with line by line explanation with *unordered_map* and *backtracking.***  I will try to post my detailed solution of daily leetcoding challenge everyday in CPP. 
```
class Solution {
/*
IDEA: 
1) Count number of occurences of each node in a path and map it in an uordered_map.
2) If a node has left and right children both as NULL, then we have to check if the 
   permutation of path is palindrome or not.
        => Traverse through the map and check if the nodes frequency are multiple of 2.
        => Allow only one node to have odd frequency
3) We have to backtrack the frequency of nodes in our map, once we have considered it.
4) In case if a node has only children, when we encounter a NULL leaf node we simple have 
   to return and do not computation.
*/

public:
    void solve(TreeNode* node, unordered_map<int, int>& path, int& res){

        //NULL child of a node only having 1 children
        if(node == NULL) return;

        //If we reach the last node i.e. one path is completed
        if(node->left == NULL && node->right == NULL){

            //Since we entered the base condition we have to manually increase 
            //the frequency of the current leaf node in our map.
            ++path[node->val];

            //'allow' var will help us to have one node freq as odd.
            //'update' var will tell if the path is palindrome of not. If true, then only
            //final res value be incremented by 1.

            bool allow = true, update = true;

            for(auto i : path){
                if(i.second % 2 == 0) continue;

                //Only node is allowed to have odd frequency.
                if(i.second % 2 != 0 && allow) {
                    allow = false;
                    continue;
                }

                //If more than 1 nodes have odd frequency, then do not have palindromic
                //path, hence the res should not be updated.
                else {
                    update = false;
                    break;
                }
            }

            //If path is palindromic, update the res
            if(update) ++res;

            //Backtrack the current leaf node manually by decreasing its frequency in
            //the map.
            --path[node->val];
            return;
        }

        //Add the current node in the map and increase its frequency if already present
        ++path[node->val];

        solve(node->left, path, res);
        solve(node->right, path, res);

        //Once both the children of node is explored, decrease the freq of node by 1.
        --path[node->val];
    }

    int pseudoPalindromicPaths (TreeNode* root) {
        int res = 0;
        unordered_map<int, int> path;
        solve(root, path, res);
        return res;
    }
};
```

