solutions.content:
#### Brute-Force Approach : 
We have to first store the values of all nodes of any path from root node to leaf node and then check if that can be used to make a palindrome or not. If it is a palindrome then we can just add 1 to our answer. We have to do the same for every path and then return the final answer.
#### Palindrome Checking
For this we can use a map/vector for storing values and for finding just we have to check the numbers having odd occurences. If there is more than one number having odd occurence in a path then it can't be used to make a palindrome.
How are we determing that At most one odd occurence in a path is required for palindrome ?? 
If there are all numbers having even number of occurences then the total elements in the path will be even and we can arrange them into a palindromic fashion. If there is one number having odd number of occurences then we can put that into middle and arrange the remaining numbers into a palindromic fashion, But if there is more than one number having odd occurences then we can't make a palindrome out of that by any means.
#### Efficient Solution :
We can do this without storing the whole path !! Yes You read it right. 
We will use the fact that either the occurence of number appearing in the path can be odd or even. 
Using a set will make our job easier for us. We will only store the numbers having odd occurences in a path. Initially all the occurences are 0, so our set is empty.
Whenever we counter a number for the path if it is already in the set we will remove that and if it is not in the set then we will insert it ninto the set.
**Time complexity** of this is **O(N)** : Number of Nodes in the tree
**Space Complexity** of this is **O(1)** : At max there can be 9 numbers in the set because the node value varies from 1 to 9 only.
```
	// Declaring a set which will store the occurences and a global answer variable.

	int ans = 0;
    set<int> s;

	// Toogle will insert a value in the set if its not already present and will remove otherwise.

    void toggle(TreeNode* root) {
        if(s.find(root->val)!= s.end()) s.erase(root->val);
        else s.insert(root->val);
    }

	// dfs function is the recursive calling of the function for all the nodes to get the path

    void dfs(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) return;
        toggle(root);    // Inserting the node into the path
        if(root->left == nullptr && root->right == nullptr) {
            if(s.size() < 2) ans++; 
            toggle(root);    // Backtracking i.e. removing the node from path
            return;
        }
        dfs(root->left);
        dfs(root->right);
        toggle(root);     // Backtracking i.e. removing the node from path
    }
    int pseudoPalindromicPaths (TreeNode* root) {
        dfs(root);
